         }\n                      #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n                    }\n                    #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n                  }\n                  #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n                }\n                #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n              }\n              #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n            }\n            #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n          }\n          #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n        }\n        #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n      }\n      #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n    }\n    #endif\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n  }\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n  float dstN = posM.x - posN.x;\n  float dstP = posP.x - posM.x;\n  if(!horzSpan) dstN = posM.y - posN.y;\n  if(!horzSpan) dstP = posP.y - posM.y;\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n  bool goodSpanN = (lumaEndN < 0.0f) != lumaMLTZero;\n  float spanLength = (dstP + dstN);\n  bool goodSpanP = (lumaEndP < 0.0f) != lumaMLTZero;\n  float spanLengthRcp = 1.0f/spanLength;\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n  bool directionN = dstN < dstP;\n  float dstMin = min(dstN, dstP);\n  bool goodSpan = directionN ? goodSpanN : goodSpanP;\n  float subpixG = subpixF * subpixF;\n  float pixelOffset = (dstMin * (-spanLengthRcp)) + 0.5f;\n  float subpixH = subpixG * fxaaQualitySubpix;\n/*--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\n  float pixelOffsetGood = goodSpan ? pixelOffset : 0.0f;\n  float pixelOffsetSubpix = max(pixelOffsetGood, subpixH);\n  if(!horzSpan) posM.x += pixelOffsetSubpix * lengthSign;\n  if( horzSpan) posM.y += pixelOffsetSubpix * lengthSign;\n  PS_OUT( fxaaTexTop( t_sSrc, s_tSrc, posM));\n}\n/*==========================================================================*/\n""

""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.GameCameraFOV=Game camera FOV""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.GameCameraFOVHint=FOV angle for the in game camera.\nMay be different from the real world camera FOV.""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.CameraAdjustments=This step allows you to slightly adjust the camera offset in order to rectify the imperfect camera calibration performed earlier.\nPlace the controller (any will do) so it is located between the tracked headset and the camera and tweak the settings to try to get a better match between the controller in the video feed and the one rendered by the game.\nIn case this offset is too large or you struggle to adjust it, you should go back and repeat the camera calibration step.""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.CameraCalibration=This step will make sure that the physical camera matches the in game camera and vice versa. It is important that this step is performed very carefully in order to avoid the pain of manual camera calibration (which is possible but should be avoided).\nFirst you need to decide whether you will be using a camera that is static (on a fixed position) or you'll want to move the camera during recording. You should definitely use a static camera if you don't have a third controller to spare (that is connected via a USB cable).\nSimply select either the static camera configuration or one of the paired controllers that is attached to the physical camera.\nIn case you're not sure whether the selected controller is really attached to the camera, you can use the 'Identify camera controller' button so you can verify whether you have selected the correct controller.\n\nOnce you are satisfied with the camera controller setup, you should continue to actual camera calibration.\nCamera calibration is performed by initially standing fairly close and facing the camera and moving one controller (any paired controller that is not attached to the camera) so that you align the hole at the top of the controller with the crosshair displayed on the screen that displays the mirrored picture from the camera (you should observe yourself in that image like in a mirror to verify you are perfectly aligning the controller). Then press the trigger button on the controller you are holding for alignment to mark the current sample and repeat this procedure using the same controller until you mark all five calibration points while standing near the camera.\nThen you will be asked to move further away from the camera and repeat the same steps at a distance.\n\nIn case you have already performed these steps in the past and are satisfied with the previous configurations you may skip this step in order to modify some other settings using this wizard interface.\n""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.ChromaKey=Now you need to set up the chroma key parameters. Chose the chroma key color and adjust other parameters that work for your current setup.""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.ControllerAdjustment=Video feed has some latency compared to the game which looks bad: controller or weapons in game seem to rush ahead of the player in the video feed. The good news is that we can compensate this delay by delaying the controller (and consequently weapon) position in mixed reality view. This delay depends on a number of different things and should be tweaked for your particular setup by adjusting the time (in milliseconds) the controller appears to be in the past in order to match the video.\nTo perform this step, make sure you wave the controller (any will do) between the camera and the tracked headset while observing the delay between the feed and the controller rendered in game. Adjust the delay until the rendered controller perfectly matches the controller in the video feed.""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.ImposterAdjustment=Player imposter is a rectangle rendered in the scene that contains a part of chroma keyed video feed which is intended to represent the player inside the game.\nSince the lighting of the player in the studio generally doesn't match the lighting in the game level, we often need to ajust the player imposter brightness in order to lighten or darken the player.\n\nIn this step you can also adjust the part of the video feed that is used for player imposter, by adjusting the imposter height and width. Since player imposter is always centered around the center of the player (a point between the headset and the floor), by limiting the imposter height and width, we can cut away the part of the scene that is not near the player. This allows us to have a studio not entirely covered by the green screen - green screen just needs to cover the player.""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.InputSelection=At this stage you need to select video capture device and format before you can proceed. So make sure you're seeing the expected feed in this window before you continue.\n\nIMPORTANT NOTE: You don't need any special software for mixed reality in this game - the game does it all. So make sure you quit any other software that might be using the camera before you proceed.""
""ETRSMenu.MixedReality.Help.MiscSettings=Here you can change some useful but not essential options. For most, the defaults should work just fine.\n\nPlay space rotation is very useful when you want to change the general direction where player should be facing most of the time during recording (if you want to record the player from a different angle).\n\nYou probably don't want to render aim lasers in mixed reality as they are tied to player's weapon position which is generally ahead of the weapon shown in mixed reality view (due to latency compensation).\n\nUnless you have some kind of physical weapon you want to record in mixed reality, you should not skip weapon rendering in mixed reality.""

""local bEnabled = net_bEnableDynamicFlowControl\n\nlocal function SetLimits()\n\t-- set limitless upper boundary\n\tcli_iMaxBPS = 1000000\n\tcli_iMaxOutBPS = 1000000\n\tser_iMaxClientBPS = 1000000\nend\n\nif globals.bEnableDynamicFlowControlStarted then\n\tSetLimits()\n\tglobals.bEnableDynamicFlowControlStarted = false\n\tWait(Delay(2))\nend\n\nlocal function printDBG(strPrintString)\n  if globals.netDebugFlowControlPrintEnabled == true then\n    print(strPrintString)\n  end\nend\n\nprintDBG(\"Dynamic flow control started\")\n\nglobals.bEnableDynamicFlowControlStarted = bEnabled\n\nlocal function CalculateNewBPS(fPacketLoss, ulPing, ulCurrentBPS)\n\tlocal fBPSInflationFactor  = 1 \n\tif fPacketLoss < 0.05 then\n\t\tfBPSInflationFactor = mthLerpF(1, 0.95, fPacketLoss / 0.05)\n\telse\n\t\tfBPSInflationFactor = mthLerpF(0.99, 0.85, fPacketLoss - 0.05)\n\tend\n\t\n\tif ulPing > 150 then\n\t\tlocal ulPingClamped = mthClampF(ulPing, 0, 500)\n\t\tfBPSInflationFactor = mthLerpF(1, 0.8, ulPingClamped / 500)\n\tend\n\t\n\tif fBPSInflationFactor == 1 then\n\t\tulCurrentBPS = ulCurrentBPS + 1000\n\tend\n\t\n\tprintDBG(\"Inflation Factor = \" .. fBPSInflationFactor)\n\treturn ulCurrentBPS * fBPSInflationFactor\nend\n\nlocal bJustStarted = true\nlocal bLimitsInitialized = false\n\nwhile net_bEnableDynamicFlowControl do\n\tfor i = 0, netObtainNumberOfConnections() -1 do\n\t\tif bJustStarted then\n\t\t\t-- start slow than adjust\n\t\t\tnetSetOutBPS(i, 6000)\n\t\tend\n\t\tlocal fPacketLoss, ulPing, ulCurrentBPS\n\t\tfPacketLoss, ulPing, ulCurrentBPS = netObtainNetworkFlowInfo(i)\n\t\tprintDBG(\"Connection index = \" .. i .. \n\t\t\" PacketLossRate = \" .. fPacketLoss .. \n\t\t\" PingMS = \" .. ulPing .. \n\t\t\" CurrentBPS = \" .. ulCurrentBPS)  \n\t\t\n\t\tnetSetOutBPS(i, CalculateNewBPS(fPacketLoss, ulPing, ulCurrentBPS))\n\tend\n\t--flow will be controled so we don't need limits\n\n\tif not bLimitsInitialized then\n\t\tbLimitsInitialized = true\n\t\tSetLimits()\n\tend\n\t\n\tWait(Delay(1))\n\tbJustStarted = false\nend\n\nbLimitsInitialized = false\n\nprintDBG(\"Dynamic flow control ended\")\n""

""TEXTURE2DMS""
""Texture2DMS<float4,SUB_SAMPLES> t_tTexture: register(t0); \nconst uniform float4 c_vTexMultiviewSize: register(c0); \nstruct PS_INPUT { \n  float2 vTex : TEXCOORD0; \n  uint iViewport : SV_ViewportArrayIndex; \n}; \nfloat4 main( PS_INPUT i) : SV_Target { \n  SetVRViewport(i.iViewport); \n  float4 vOutColor = float4( 0,0,0, 0); \n  float2 vTex = MultiviewCoordConditional(i.vTex, c_vTexMultiviewSize.yz, c_vTexMultiviewSize.x); \n#if BILINEAR_FILTER \n  float4 vCoords = vTex.xyxy+ float4( -0.495f,-0.495f, 0.495f,0.495f); \n#endif \n  for( int iSample=0; iSample<SUB_SAMPLES; iSample++) { \n    float4 vSubSample; \n    #if BILINEAR_FILTER \n      vSubSample  = t_tTexture.Load( vCoords.xy, iSample); // UL \n      vSubSample += t_tTexture.Load( vCoords.xw, iSample); // DL \n      vSubSample += t_tTexture.Load( vCoords.zw, iSample); // DR \n      vSubSample += t_tTexture.Load( vCoords.zy, iSample); // UR \n      vSubSample *= 0.25f; \n    #else \n      vSubSample = t_tTexture.Load( vTex, iSample); \n    #endif \n    vOutColor += vSubSample; \n  } \n  vOutColor /= SUB_SAMPLES; \n  return vOutColor; \n}; \n""
